{{Infobox football biography | name = Xande Silva | image = | caption = | fullname = Alexandre Nascimento Costa Silva | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1997|3|16|df=yes}} | birth_place = [[Porto]], Portugal | height = {{Height|m=1.77}} | position = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]] | currentclub = [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] | clubnumber = 32 | youthyears1 = 2007–2008 | youthclubs1 = [[F.C. Alverca|Alverca]] | youthyears2 = 2008–2009 | youthclubs2 = [[C.F. Os Belenenses|Belenenses]] | youthyears3 = 2009–2014 | youthclubs3 = [[Sporting Clube de Portugal|Sporting CP]] | youthyears4 = 2014–2015 | youthclubs4 = [[Vitória S.C.|Vitória Guimarães]] | years1 = 2014–2018 | clubs1 = [[Vitória S.C. B|Vitória Guimarães B]] | caps1 = 52 | goals1 = 4 | years2 = 2015–2018 | clubs2 = [[Vitória S.C.|Vitória Guimarães]] | caps2 = 26 | goals2 = 1 | years3 = 2018– | clubs3 = [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] | caps3 = 1 | goals3 = 0 | nationalyears1 = 2012 | nationalteam1 = Portugal U15 | nationalcaps1 = 2 | nationalgoals1 = 1 | nationalyears2 = 2012–2013 | nationalteam2 = [[Portugal national under-16 football team|Portugal U16]] | nationalcaps2 = 11 | nationalgoals2 = 3 | nationalyears3 = 2013–2014 | nationalteam3 = [[Portugal national under-17 football team|Portugal U17]] | nationalcaps3 = 15 | nationalgoals3 = 4 | nationalyears4 = 2014 | nationalteam4 = [[Portugal national under-18 football team|Portugal U18]] | nationalcaps4 = 2 | nationalgoals4 = 1 | nationalyears5 = 2015–2016 | nationalteam5 = [[Portugal national under-19 football team|Portugal U19]] | nationalcaps5 = 21 | nationalgoals5 = 5 | nationalyears6 = 2016–2017 | nationalteam6 = [[Portugal national under-20 football team|Portugal U20]] | nationalcaps6 = 14 | nationalgoals6 = 5 | club-update = 16:08, 30 December 2018 (UTC) | nationalteam-update = }} '''Alexandre 'Xande' Nascimento Costa Silva''' (born 16 March 1997) is a Portuguese [[Association football|footballer]] who plays for English club [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]].
==Club career== ===Vitória Guimarães=== Born in [[Porto]], Silva joined [[Vitória S.C.|Vitória de Guimarães]]' academy at the age of 17 after a five-year spell at [[Sporting CP]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.supersporting.net/golos-de-xande-ganham-projeccao/|title=Golos de Xande ganham projecção|trans-title=Xande goals making a name|publisher=Super Sporting|last=Augusto|first=Fernando|language=Portuguese|date=6 March 2013|accessdate=2 November 2018}}</ref> He started his senior career with [[Vitória S.C. B|the former's reserves]], making his [[Segunda Liga]] debut on 17 August 2014 by coming on as a late [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] in a 0–1 away loss against [[U.D. Oliveirense|Oliveirense]];<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.record.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/2--liga/detalhe/oliveirense-v-guimaraes-b-1-0-golo-de-sergio-da-o-triunfo-900285|title=Oliveirense-V. Guimarães B, 1–0: Golo de Sérgio dá o triunfo|trans-title=Oliveirense-V. Guimarães B, 1–0: Sérgio goal gives win|newspaper=[[Record (newspaper)|Record]]|language=Portuguese|date=17 August 2014|accessdate=2 November 2018}}</ref> he scored his first goal in the competition the following 18 January, helping the hosts beat [[S.L. Benfica B|Benfica B]] 4–1.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ojogo.pt/futebol/2a-liga/noticias/interior/vguimaraes-b-goleou-benfica-b-4349014.html|title=V.Guimarães B goleou Benfica B|trans-title=V.Guimarães B routed Benfica B|newspaper=[[O Jogo]]|language=Portuguese|date=18 January 2015|accessdate=2 November 2018}}</ref>
Silva's first appearance in the [[Primeira Liga]] took place in the penultimate match of [[2014–15 Primeira Liga|the season]], and he played 11 minutes in a 0–0 home draw to [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]] after replacing [[Otávio Edmilson da Silva Monteiro|Otávio]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rtp.pt/noticias/desporto/benfica-campeao-nacional_e829316|title=Reportagem V. Guimarães 0–0 Benfica|trans-title=V. Guimarães 0–0 Benfica match report|publisher=[[Rádio e Televisão de Portugal]]|language=Portuguese|date=17 May 2015|accessdate=2 November 2018}}</ref> His maiden league goal occurred on 7 December 2015, in a 3–1 home defeat of [[Rio Ave F.C.|Rio Ave]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tsf.pt/desporto/interior/-vitoria-de-guimaraes-vence-rio-ave-4920044.html|title=Vitória de Guimarães vence Rio Ave|trans-title=Vitória de Guimarães beat Rio Ave|publisher=[[TSF (radio station)|TSF]]|language=Portuguese|date=7 December 2015|accessdate=2 November 2018}}</ref>
===West Ham United=== Silva joined [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] for an undisclosed fee on 2 August 2018,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whufc.com/news/articles/2018/august/02-august/west-ham-united-sign-promising-portuguese-forward-xande-silva|title=West Ham United sign promising Portuguese forward Xande Silva|publisher=West Ham United F.C.|date=2 August 2018|accessdate=2 August 2018}}</ref> signing a three-year contract and being recruited initially for the [[West Ham United F.C. Under-23s and Academy|under-23 team]]. He scored a four-minute [[hat-trick]] on his [[Premier League 2]] debut 11 days later, against [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C. Under-23s and Academy|Tottenham Hotspur]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/2018/august/pl2-report-spurs-1-3-west-ham/|title=Under-23s sunk by quickfire treble|publisher=Tottenham Hotspur|date=13 August 2018|accessdate=2 November 2018}}</ref><ref name=London>{{Cite web|url=https://www.football.london/west-ham-united-fc/transfer-news/xande-silva-west-ham-transfers-14984081|title=Who is Xande Silva? West Ham's newest goalscoring sensation who put Tottenham to the sword|publisher=Football London|last=Inkersole|first=Sam|date=14 August 2018|accessdate=15 August 2018}}</ref>
Silva made his [[Premier League]] debut on 30 December 2018 in a 0–2 away defeat to [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]], coming on as a second-half substitute for [[Marko Arnautović]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46663364|title=Burnley 2–0 West Ham United|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|last=Sutcliffe|first=Steve|date=30 December 2018|accessdate=30 December 2018}}</ref>
==International career== Silva was [[Cap (sport)|capped]] by [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]] at every youth level between under-15 and [[Portugal national under-20 football team|under-20]]. He was part of the [[Portugal national under-17 football team|under-17 squad]] that reached the semi-finals of the [[2014 UEFA European Under-17 Championship|2014 UEFA European Championship]], and was named in the Team of the Tournament.<ref>{{cite document|url=http://www.uefa.com/under17/season=2014/technical-report/tr-under17-2014.pdf|title=Technical report|publisher=UEFA|page=21|dead-url=yes|accessdate=15 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170914014819/http://www.uefa.com/under17/season=2014/technical-report/tr-under17-2014.pdf|archivedate=14 September 2017}}</ref>
Two years later, Silva helped the [[Portugal national under-19 football team|under-19 team]] to the semi-finals of the [[2016 UEFA European Under-19 Championship|2016 European Championship]] in Germany.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/under19/season=2016/matches/round=2000599/match=2020325/index.html|title=Under-19 – Portugal-France|publisher=UEFA|accessdate=15 August 2018}}</ref> He was then selected by under-20 manager [[Emílio Peixe]] for the [[2017 FIFA U-20 World Cup]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvi24.iol.pt/selecao-portugal/selecao-sub-20/os-convocados-da-selecao-nacional-para-o-mundial-sub-20|title=Os convocados da Seleção Nacional para o Mundial Sub-20|trans-title=The national team picks for the Under-20 World Cup|publisher=[[TVI 24]]|last=Gomes de Andrade|first=Maria|language=Portuguese|date=2 May 2017|accessdate=2 November 2018}}</ref> where he scored in the quarter-final against [[Uruguay national under-20 football team|Uruguay]], which they lost after a [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shootout]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/u20worldcup/matches/round=275956/match=300367044/match-report.html|title=Uruguay progress, Portugal pay the penalty|publisher=FIFA|date=4 June 2017|accessdate=2 November 2018}}</ref><ref name=London/>
==Personal life== Silva's father, [[Joaquim Alberto Silva|Joaquim]], was also a footballer. Also a forward, he spent most of his career in China and Portugal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maisfutebol.iol.pt/alexandre-silva/selecao/filho-de-quinzinho-e-internacional-portugues-e-inspira-se-em-balotelli|title=Filho de Quinzinho é internacional português e inspira-se em Balotelli|trans-title=Son of Quinzinho is a Portuguese international and draws inspiration from Balotelli|publisher=Mais Futebol|last=Calhau|first=Pedro|language=Portuguese|date=3 April 2014|accessdate=2 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ojogo.pt/futebol/taca-portugal/noticias/interior/amp/quinzinho-adivinhou-encontro-com-filho-nos-oitavos-5517243.html|title=Quinzinho, treinador-adjunto do Vilafranquense, disse no fim de semana ao filho, Xande Silva, jogador de Vitória de Guimarães, que se iam encontrar nos "oitavos" e que lhe ia ganhar|trans-title=Quinzinho, Vilafranquense assistant coach, told this weekend his son, Alexandre Silva, Vitória de Guimarães player, that they would meet in "last-16" and he would beat him|newspaper=O Jogo|language=Portuguese|date=24 November 2016|accessdate=2 November 2018}}</ref>
